06447nam a22009015i 9780292798601DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212003txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927986017 a10.7560/7124472doi  a(DE-B1597)587609  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1435.3.A6bM37 2003 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a972.81/01622100aMaya Palaces and Elite Residences :bAn Interdisciplinary Approach /ced. by Jessica Joyce Christie. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Elite Residences at Blue Creek, Belize -- tChapter Two. At Court in Copan -- tChapter Three. A Multipurpose Structure in the Late Classic Palace at Copan -- tChapter Four. Palaces of the Royal Court at Tikal -- tChapter Five. The Political Acquisition of Sacred Geography -- tChapter Six. Where Did Elites Live? -- tChapter Seven. Access Patterns in Maya Royal Precincts -- tChapter Eight. Evidence for the Functions and Meanings of Some Northern Maya Palaces -- tChapter Nine. The Function of a Maya Palace at Yaxuna -- tChapter Ten. Palace and Society in the Northern Maya Lowlands -- tChapter Eleven. The Tripartite Layout of Rooms in Maya Elite Residences -- tChapter Twelve. Conclusions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaya "palaces" have intrigued students of this ancient Mesoamerican culture since the early twentieth century, when scholars first applied the term "palace" to multi-room, gallery-like buildings set on low platforms in the centers of Maya cities. Who lived in these palaces? What types of ceremonial and residential activities took place there? How do the physical forms and spatial arrangement of the buildings embody Maya concepts of social organization and cosmology? This book brings together state-of-the-art data and analysis regarding the occupants, ritual and residential uses, and social and cosmological meanings of Maya palaces and elite residences. A multidisciplinary team of senior researchers reports on sites in Belize (Blue Creek), Western Honduras (Copan), the Peten (Tikal, Dos Pilas, Aguateca), and the Yucatan (Uxmal, Chichen-Itza, Dzibilchaltun, Yaxuna). Archaeologist contributors discuss the form of palace buildings and associated artifacts, their location within the city, and how some palaces related to landscape features. Their approach is complemented by art historical analyses of architectural sculpture, epigraphy, and ethnography. Jessica Joyce Christie concludes the volume by identifying patterns and commonalties that apply not only to the cited examples, but also to Maya architecture in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMaya architecture. 0aMayasxDwellings. 0aMayasxKings and rulers. 0aPalaceszLatin America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aAmbrosino, James N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrews V, E. Wyllys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Jessica Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Jessica Joyce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDemarest, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoonan, William F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscobedo, Héctor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverson, Gloria E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuderjan, Thomas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanratty, C.